concat.haxe_doc: Returns a new Array by appending [a] to [this].

splice.haxe_doc: Removes [len] elements starting from [pos] an returns them.

unshift.haxe_doc: Adds the element [x] at the start of the array.

iterator.haxe_doc: Returns an iterator of the Array values.

class.haxe_doc: An Array is a storage for values. You can access it using indexes or with its API. On the server side, it's often better to use a [List] which is less memory and CPU consuming, unless you really need indexed access.

now.haxe_doc: Returns a Date representing the current local time.

fromTime.haxe_doc: Returns a Date from a timestamp [t] which is the number of milliseconds elapsed since 1st January 1970.

getSeconds.haxe_doc: Returns the seconds of the date (0-59 range).

getMonth.haxe_doc: Returns the month of the date (0-11 range).

getDate.haxe_doc: Returns the day of the date (1-31 range).

getDay.haxe_doc: Returns the week day of the date (0-6 range).

toString.haxe_doc: Returns a string representation for the Date, by using the standard format [YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS]. See [DateTools.format] for other formating rules.

class.haxe_doc: The Date class is used for date manipulation. There is some extra functions available in the [DateTools] class.

matchedRight.haxe_doc: Returns the part of the string that was at the right of of the matched substring.

matchedPos.haxe_doc: Returns the position of the matched substring within the original matched string.

replace.haxe_doc: Replaces a pattern by another string. The [by] format can contains [$1] to [$9] that will correspond to groups matched while replacing. [$$] means the [$] character.

customReplace.haxe_doc: For each occurence of the pattern in the string [s], the function [f] is called and can return the string that needs to be replaced. All occurences are matched anyway, and setting the [g] flag might cause some incorrect behavior on some platforms.

new.haxe_doc: Creates a new regular expression with pattern [r] and options [opt].

class.haxe_doc: Regular expressions are a way to find regular patterns into Strings. Have a look at the tutorial on haXe website to learn how to use them.

split.haxe_doc: Split the string using the specified delimiter.

halted.haxe_doc: * Indicates whether the bond has been halted (true) or not (false). See the halt method for more information.

willDestroyOnUse.haxe_doc: * Indicates whether the bond will be destroyed right after it is used (true) or not (false).

destroy.haxe_doc: * Destroys the bond. The signaler that created this bond will no longer notify listeners through it. Bond cannot be * "undestroyed". To temporary suspend the bond from notifying the associated listener, use the halt method.

destroyOnUse.haxe_doc: * Destroys the bond right after it is used. Whether this bond has already been used at the moment this method is called does * not matter: the bond will be destroyed on its first use after this method has been called. This method returns this bond * itself.

halt.haxe_doc: * Halts the bond. The bond will ignore any calls, and will not notify any listeners, until the resume method is called. If * the bond was already halted, calling this method has no effect.

resume.haxe_doc: * Resumes the bond, after it has been halted by calling the halt method. If the bond was not halted, calling this method has * no effect. See the halt method for more information.

class.haxe_doc: * A bond represents the connection between a signaler and a listener. Bonds are created when listeners add themselves to a * signaler. * * Bonds are used internally, and can be ignored in common cases. However, sometimes it is useful for listeners to store the * bond in a variable. Doing so allows you to halt and resume the bond, and destroy it easily.

subject.haxe_doc: * The subject this signaler belongs to.

addBubblingTarget.haxe_doc:
* Adds a bubbling target to the signaler. The signaler will bubble to this bubbling target in bubbling processes. * *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0, or as3-signals by Robert Penner: those systems do not have an * equivalent to this method, as they don't allow you to manually define where events/signals bubble to. *

addNotificationTarget.haxe_doc:
* Adds a notification target to the signaler. The signaler will notify to this notification target in bubbling processes, * however, the data inside the signal will not be passed to this notification target. * *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0, or as3-signals by Robert Penner: those systems do not have an * equivalent to this method, as they don't allow you to manually define where events/signals bubble to. *

bind.haxe_doc:
* Binds this signaler to a listener function that accepts an argument of the datatype of this signaler, and returns nothing. * Returns the bond between the signaler. The bond can be removed by calling either the unbind method of the signaler, or the * destroy method of the returned bond. * *
  • * If you are familiar with jQuery: this method is similar to the "bind" method of that library. *
  • * If you are familiar with as3-signals by Robert Penner: this method is similar to the "add" method of that library. *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0: this method is similar to the "addEventListener" method of that * system, though the bindAdvanced method of this library has more similarities to addEventListener. *

bindAdvanced.haxe_doc:
* Binds this signaler to a listener function that accepts a signal, and returns nothing. Returns the bond between the * signaler. The bond can be removed by calling either the unbindAdvanced method of the signaler, or the destroy method of * the returned bond. * *
  • * If you are familiar with jQuery: this method is similar to the "bind" method of that library. *
  • * If you are familiar with as3-signals by Robert Penner: this method is similar to the "add" method of that library, though * the bind method of this library has more similarities to add. *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0: this method is similar to the "addEventListener" method of that * system. *

bindVoid.haxe_doc:
* Binds this signaler to a listener function that accepts nothing, and returns nothing. Returns the bond between the * signaler. The bond can be removed by calling either the unbindVoid method of the signaler, or the destroy method of the * returned bond. * *
  • * If you are familiar with jQuery: this method is similar to the "bind" method of that library. *
  • * If you are familiar with as3-signals by Robert Penner: this method is similar to the "add" method of that library, though * the bind method of this library has more similarities to add. *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0: this method is similar to the "addEventListener" method of that * system, though the bindAdvanced method of this library has more similarities to addEventListener. *

dispatch.haxe_doc: * Dispatches a signal, containing the passed data. All the listeners that are listening to this signaler will be notified. * The signal will bubble to all of the bubbling targets that were added to this signaler. This method may only be called * by the subject of the signaler.

removeBubblingTarget.haxe_doc: * Removes a bubbling target from the signaler. The signaler will stop bubbling to this bubbling target. If the signaler * does not have the passed value as a bubbling target, calling this method has no effect.

removeNotificationTarget.haxe_doc: * Removes a notification target from the signaler. The signaler will stop notifying this notification target. If the * signaler does not have the passed value as a notification target, calling this method has no effect.

unbind.haxe_doc: * Removed the bond between this signaler and a listener. If such bond does not exist, calling this method has no effect.

unbindAdvanced.haxe_doc: * Removed the bond between this signaler and a listener. If such bond does not exist, calling this method has no effect.

unbindVoid.haxe_doc: * Removed the bond between this signaler and a listener. If such bond does not exist, calling this method has no effect.

class.haxe_doc:
* A signalers is a tool, used by a subject to notify its environment (listeners). Subjects create their signalers, usually in * their constructors. Listeners add themselves to signalers by calling one of the binding methods. * *
  • * If you are familiar with as3-signals by Robert Penner: signalers are similar to "signals" in that library. *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0: signalers have some similarities to "event dispatchers" in that system. * There is one major difference, though: an event dispatcher can dispatch events of different event types; but in this library * each type of signal has its own signaler. *

subjectClassNames.haxe_doc: * The fully qualified class names of the subject.

getOrigin.haxe_doc: * Returns the passed origin if it is not null. Returns the subject of this signaler if the passed origin is null.

verifyCaller.haxe_doc: * Checks whether the class name inside the passed position information equals the class name of the subject of this * signaler. Used in the dispatch method, as that method may only be called by the subject. * * Two notes. * One, by using this method you check whether the caller is of the same type as the subject, which does not necessarily mean * it's the same instance. This is the expected behavior, as it is consistent with private members. * Two, one could hack his or her way around this check. How to do this should be obvious. The check is not designed to be * unhackable; rather it is designed to prevent developers from accidentally misapplying HSL. Nicolas Cannasse once said * "everything should be made accessible, if you know what you're doing".

new.haxe_doc: * Creates a new direct signaler. * * The passed subject will be used as the subject of this signaler. Only the subject is allowed to call the dispatch method. * Signals dispatched by this signaler will have the subject as current target, and in some cases as origin. * * If the reject null data flag is set, the signaler will throw an exception if the subject attempts to dispatch a signal * with null as data, or the the signaler is about to bubble a signal that contains null as data.

class.haxe_doc: * A signaler that dispatches signals directly.

callListener.haxe_doc: * Calls the listener stored inside. Classes that extend this one should override this method.

determineEquals.haxe_doc: * Determines whether the passed bond equals this one. Returns true if they are equal; false otherwise. Classes that extend * this one should override this method.

class.haxe_doc: * A doubly linked bond. The bond has a reference to the next and the previous bond in the list.

isConnected.haxe_doc: * Indicates whether this sentinel is connected to other bonds (true), or not (false).

add.haxe_doc: * Inserts a bond between the sentinel and the previous bond. Effectively, the newely added bond ends up being the last one * in the list.

getIsConnected.haxe_doc: * Determines whether this sentinel is connected to other bonds (true), or not (false).

remove.haxe_doc: * Removes a bond connected to the sentinel. * * The sentinel will look for the first bond equal to the passed value connected to it, and destroy it.

class.haxe_doc: * A sentinel "bond". The sentinel is not a real bond, as it does not bind the signaler to a listener. Rather it is the value * before the first bond and after the last bond of this signaler. It contains logic that helps the signaler working with the * linked list structure.
* A regular bond is a bond that is created in result of a call to the bind method.
* A niladic bond is a bond that is created in result of a call to the bindVoid method.
* An advanced bond is a bond that is created in result of a call to the bindAdvanced method.

currentBond.haxe_doc: * The bond that is currently processing the signal.

data.haxe_doc: * The data element in this signal.

data1.haxe_doc: * Deprecated. Equal to the data property.

immediatePropagationStopped.haxe_doc: * Indicates whether stopImmediatePropagation method was called on this signal (true) or not (false).

origin.haxe_doc:
* The subject that initially dispatched this signal. For instance, if a user clicks on a button that is inside a menu, and * signals bubble from that button to that menu, the currentTarget will be the button at some point and the menu at another. * The origin will constantly be the button. In other words, the origin is the subject that called the dispatch method. * *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0, jQuery, or any other system that was based on DOM level 3 events: * this property is similar to the target property of the event objects in those systems. *

propagationStopped.haxe_doc: * Indicates whether stopPropagation method was called on this signal (true) or not (false). stopPropagation calls on other * signals, even in the same dispatch process, don't influence this property.

stopPropagation.haxe_doc:
* Stops the bubbling of the signal. The subject currently dispatching this signal (as found in the target property of this * the signal) will not bubble it to its bubbling targets. Calling this method does not prevent other listeners of the same * signaler from being called: see stopImmediatePropagation for that functionality. * *
  • * If you are familiar with events in ActionScript 3.0, jQuery, or any other system that was based on DOM level 3 events: * this method is similar to the stopPropagation method of the event objects in those systems. *

new.haxe_doc: * Creates a new signal. Signals are usually created by signalers, so this constructor will probably not be called outside of * the library itself.

class.haxe_doc: * A signal is dispatched by a subject, through a signaler. However, only listeners that were added using the bindAdvanced * method can access the actual Signal instances.
